prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: This is a continuum experiment, so we have no specific requirements for the correlator setup aside from the central frequency.

The measured half-light radii of bright z > 6 galaxies (in the rest-frame UV) are typically ~1 kpc or less (Curtis-Lake et al. 2014), corresponding to a radius of ~0.2 arcseconds. In order to avoid beam dilution, we request an angular resolution of 1 arcsecond.
Due to the small size of our target galaxies, we do not require additional observations with the ACA.

For each target galaxy, we set the total infrared luminosity equal to 4x the measured UV luminosity, similar to the small fraction of FIR-bright galaxies in Capak et al. (2015) and the dusty z ~ 7.5 galaxy in Watson et al. (2015), then compute the flux at the best-fit photometric redshift for a beta = 1.5, T_dust = 35 K modified blackbody SED. See the rightmost column in Table 1 of the Science Case for the computed fluxes which range from 181 uJy to 690 uJy.
We request a sensitivity of 52 uJy, providing S/N >= 3.5 for every target. This is sufficient for our purposes: the target positions are known to better than 1 arcsecond precision, so the false positive probability is very small. We aim only to detect our targets, leaving detailed characterization of detected targets to future observations. It is like a fishing expedition except that we know precisely where the fish should be.

We have chosen a continuum frequency of 265 GHz to optimize the survey for detecting high-redshift galaxies across a range of redshifts and dust temperatures, as shown in Figure 1 of the Science Case.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Little is known about the dust content and obscured star formation in z > 6 galaxies. The small number of existing ALMA observations at high-redshift suggest that they are dust-poor, but with a wide range of dust properties that have no apparent relation to any other measured quantity including UV luminosity, UV spectral slope, stellar mass, or Lyman-alpha emission. We propose a shallow 265 GHz continuum survey of 30 bright UV-selected z > 6 galaxies to measure the demographics of dust content and obscured star formation when the Universe was less than a billion years old.
prp:ObsProposal.prp:scientificCategoryString: Cosmology and the High Redshift Universe
